        <!-- ========== USAGE ========== -->
        <div class="tab-content" id="tab-usage" style="display:none;padding-top:32px;">
          <div class="doc-section">
            <h2 id="when-to-use" class="doc-section-title">When and Where to Use</h2>
            <p class="doc-section-subtitle">The Slider is best for selecting numeric values within a known range where exact precision is secondary to relative positioning.</p>
            <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:24px;margin-top:24px;">
              <div style="padding:24px;background:var(--prism-surface);border:1px solid var(--prism-border);border-radius:12px;">
                <h3 style="font-size:15px;font-weight:600;color:var(--prism-text);margin-bottom:16px;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:8px;"><svg width="20" height="20" fill="none" stroke="#2563eb" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg>When to use</h3>
                <ul class="doc-list" style="border:none;background:transparent;padding-left:20px;font-size:14.5px;">
                  <li style="border:none;background:transparent;margin-bottom:8px;">Users need to select a numeric value within a known range (volume, brightness, price, percentage).</li>
                  <li style="border:none;background:transparent;margin-bottom:8px;">The exact value is less important than the relative position &mdash; users adjust by feel, then read the value label.</li>
                  <li style="border:none;background:transparent;margin-bottom:8px;">The range is continuous or has many discrete steps where individual option buttons would be impractical.</li>
                  <li style="border:none;background:transparent;">Use Range type when users define a start and end within a range (price filter, date range, etc.).</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div style="padding:24px;background:var(--prism-surface);border:1px solid var(--prism-border);border-radius:12px;">
                <h3 style="font-size:15px;font-weight:600;color:var(--prism-text);margin-bottom:16px;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:8px;"><svg width="20" height="20" fill="none" stroke="#e42527" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M6 18L18 6M6 6l12 12"/></svg>When NOT to use</h3>
                <ul class="doc-list" style="border:none;background:transparent;padding-left:20px;font-size:14.5px;">
                  <li style="border:none;background:transparent;margin-bottom:8px;">Exact values required (e.g. entering a specific number) &mdash; use a Text Field with numeric type.</li>
                  <li style="border:none;background:transparent;margin-bottom:8px;">Small number of fixed options (e.g. Low / Medium / High) &mdash; use a Radio Group or Select.</li>
                  <li style="border:none;background:transparent;margin-bottom:8px;">Precise step-based selection (e.g. quantity 1&ndash;10) &mdash; consider a number input with increment/decrement buttons.</li>
                  <li style="border:none;background:transparent;">Vertical orientation &mdash; not currently modelled in this component set.</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <hr class="doc-divider"/>
          <div class="doc-section">
            <h2 id="detailed-guidelines" class="doc-section-title">Complete Do's and Don'ts</h2>
            <p class="doc-section-subtitle">Guidelines for effective slider usage across contexts.</p>
            <div class="do-dont-grid">
              <div class="do-card"><span class="card-label">Do</span><ul>
                <li><strong>Always show value label:</strong> So users know the current value.</li>
                <li><strong>Show min/max labels:</strong> Use <code>showMinMaxLabels</code> to give users range context.</li>
                <li><strong>Step markers for discrete steps:</strong> Use <code>showStepMarkers</code> when steps &le; 10.</li>
                <li><strong>Helper text for units:</strong> Use <code>showHelperText</code> to explain units or constraints (e.g. "Values in GB").</li>
                <li><strong>Range for bounded filters:</strong> Use Range type for price, date, or bounded set filters.</li>
                <li><strong>Medium for forms:</strong> Size Medium for standard form layouts.</li>
                <li><strong>Align step to granularity:</strong> Ensure <code>step</code> aligns with the granularity users actually need.</li>
                <li><strong>Use onChangeEnd:</strong> Provide <code>onChangeEnd</code> for network requests (debounce cost).</li>
              </ul></div>
              <div class="dont-card"><span class="card-label">Don't</span><ul>
                <li><strong>Don't hide value label:</strong> When the number matters to the user.</li>
                <li><strong>Don't show step markers on large ranges:</strong> A continuous 0&ndash;100 slider with markers becomes visually noisy.</li>
                <li><strong>Don't leave unit ambiguous:</strong> Always clarify the unit of measurement.</li>
                <li><strong>Don't use two Single sliders for a range:</strong> Use the Range type instead.</li>
                <li><strong>Don't use Small for touch:</strong> Prefer Large on mobile / touch-primary interfaces.</li>
                <li><strong>Don't set step=1 on huge ranges:</strong> On 0&ndash;10,000 where increments of 100 make more sense.</li>
                <li><strong>Don't fire API calls on every onChange:</strong> Use <code>onChangeEnd</code> instead.</li>
              </ul></div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <hr class="doc-divider"/>
          <div class="doc-section">
            <h2 id="related" class="doc-section-title">Related</h2>
